Read Flow — licensing and attribution
======================================

Read Flow is a multi-crate workspace released under a split license. Which
license applies depends on the component:

AGPL-3.0-or-later
-----------------
  - read-flow          (cosmic/  — the desktop application and headless server)
  - read-flow-widgets  (widgets/ — shared desktop UI widgets)
  - read-flow-core     (core/    — async SQLite backend, REST API, file scanning)

  The full text is in LICENSE-AGPL.

  These components, and any binary built from them (including the
  `read-flow` desktop app and its `--headless` server mode), are covered
  by the GNU Affero General Public License, version 3 or later. Unlike
  plain GPL, the AGPL's Section 13 also requires offering the complete
  corresponding source to users who interact with a running instance over
  a network (not just to people who receive a copy of the binary) — see
  "Why AGPL" below for why this applies here.

  Note: `read-flow-core` depends on the `mupdf` crate, which is licensed
  AGPL-3.0-only (no "or later" clause) by Artifex. When `read-flow-core`
  is built with that dependency, the AGPL-3.0-only terms govern the
  combined binary for the parts that touch mupdf, even though
  read-flow-core's own code is licensed AGPL-3.0-or-later.

MIT
---
  - provider           (provider/)
  - epub               (epub/)
  - read-flow-pwa      (pwa/)

  The full text is in LICENSE-MIT.

  These components do not depend on any AGPL/GPL code and may be reused
  under the permissive MIT terms independently of the rest of the
  workspace.


Why AGPL
--------

`read-flow-core` unconditionally depends on `mupdf` (used in
`core/src/scan/metadata.rs` and `core/src/scan/cover.rs` for PDF
metadata/cover extraction) — the Rust bindings for Artifex's MuPDF, which
is licensed AGPL-3.0-only (dual-licensed commercially by Artifex; see
https://www.mupdf.com/ for the commercial option). `read-flow-core`
previously declared MIT despite this dependency, which was inaccurate:
anyone building or distributing it always pulled in AGPL-3.0 obligations
regardless of what the crate's own metadata said.

Because `read-flow` (the desktop app / `--headless` server) links
read-flow-core and serves a REST API over a network, AGPL-3.0 §13's
source-offer requirement applies to users of a running instance, not just
to people who receive a copy of the binary. Rather than leave that
mismatched with the crate metadata, all three previously
GPL-3.0-or-later/MIT components that participate in that binary
(`read-flow`, `read-flow-widgets`, `read-flow-core`) are now licensed
AGPL-3.0-or-later, matching the obligation that already existed in
practice. Since the source has always been public on GitHub, complying
with §13 is mostly a matter of pointing users at it — see the source-code
link surfaced in the app / server (about page / footer).

Components that don't touch mupdf (`provider`, `epub`, `pwa`) have no
AGPL exposure and stay MIT.


Third-party attribution
------------------------

The PDF viewer in the desktop application (cosmic/) is derived from
COSMIC Reader by System76:

